[[en:Yin Metal Rooster]]
[[ja:辛酉]]
[[Category:pages of uncertain originality]]
[[Category:pages of uncertain originality]]
[[Category:bumping to try to fix the sexagenary stuff]][[sn:Yin Metal Rooster]][[Category:bumping to try to fix the sexagenary stuff]]

{{Sexagenary cycle comprehensive}}
'''Yin Metal Rooster''' ({{ill|辛酉|ja|辛酉}}) is one of the {{ill|Sexagenary cycle|ja|Sexagenary cycle comprehensive}}.

It is the 58th combination in the cycle, preceded by {{ill|Yang Metal Monkey|ja|庚申|zh|庚申|ko|경신|fr|Singe de métal|de|Metall-Affe|en|lt_ko=경신}}, and followed by {{ill|Yang Water Dog|ja|壬戌|zh|壬戌|ko|임술|fr|Chien de eau|de|Wasser-Hund|en|lt_ko=임술}}. In the {{ill|Yin-Yang and Five Elements theory|ja|陰陽五行思想}}, the {{ill|Heavenly Stem|ja|十干}} {{ill|Mizunoto (癸)|cdo|Gŭi (tiĕng-găng)|fr|Gui (tige céleste)|gan|癸|hak|Kui (thiên-kôn)|ja|Mizunoto|ko|계 (천간)|vi|Quý (Thiên can)|wuu|癸|za|Gveiq (diengan)|zh_min_nan|Kúi (Thian-kan)|zh_yue|癸|zh|癸|lt=Mizunoto (癸)}} represents yin {{ill|metal|ja|金}}, and the {{ill|Earthly Branch|ja|十二支}} [[Rooster (zodiac)|Rooster (雞)]] also represents yin metal, forming a {{ill|harmonious relationship|ja|比和}}.

==Yin Metal Rooster and Revolution==
{{Anchors|Xinyou Year}}
A {{ill|Gregorian calendar|ja|西暦}} year that leaves a remainder of 1 when divided by 60 is a '''Yin Metal Rooster year'''.

Yin Metal Rooster is considered to have revolutionary significance.

In the ancient Chinese texts known as {{ill|Wei Shu|ja|緯書}} (banned by Emperor {{ill|Yang of Sui|ja|煬帝}}), with surviving fragments found in {{ill|Miyoshi Kiyoyuki|ja|三善清行}}’s “{{ill|Kakumei Kanbun|ja|革命勘文}}” (collected in ''{{ill|Gunsho Ruijū|ja|群書類従}}'' vol. 26), it is written that following {{ill|Gengshen|ja|庚申}}, Yin Metal Rooster also embodies the metal element, and Xin represents yin energy, often associated with people becoming cold-hearted. Thus, a Yin Metal Rooster year is considered a year when the {{ill|Mandate of Heaven|ja|天命}} changes, marking revolutionary shifts in {{ill|dynasties|ja|王朝}}, known as the '''{{ill|Xinyou Revolution|ja|辛酉革命}}'''.

In Japan, era name changes ({{ill|Era name|ja|改元}}) during Yin Metal Rooster years were meant to prevent political upheaval. This practice started in Yin Metal Rooster of {{ill|901|ja|901年}} ({{ill|Shōtai|ja|昌泰}} 4), when scholar-official Miyoshi Kiyoyuki proposed changing the era name to '''{{ill|Engi|ja|延喜}}'''. Frequently, era names were changed consecutively in both {{ill|Gengshen|ja|庚申}} and Yin Metal Rooster years, a custom that continued until the {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治時代}}, though such a precedent does not exist in China.

{{Anchors|Xinyou Revolution}}
During the Meiji era, scholar {{ill|Naka Michiyo|ja|那珂通世}} referenced ''Kakumei Kanbun'' with {{ill|Zheng Xuan|ja|鄭玄}}’s annotation: 
* “The way of Heaven is not distant; after every three and five, it returns. Six cycles ({{ill|Jiazi|ja|甲子}}) form one era, four sixes and two sixes overlap, and three sevens multiply to form 21 cycles, totaling 1,320 years.”

Based on this, it was believed that every '''1,260 years''' (21 cycles × 60 years = 1,260, called ''Ichibu'') there would be a major revolution during a Yin Metal Rooster year. Applying this, Naka theorized that the 9th year of {{ill|Empress Suiko|ja|推古天皇}}’s reign ({{ill|601|ja|601年}}) marked such a revolutionary year, suggesting that Emperor {{ill|Jimmu|ja|神武天皇}}’s enthronement occurred 1,260 years earlier, in {{ill|660 BC|ja|紀元前660年}}.

Alternatively, some interpret the annotation as indicating a '''1,320-year cycle''' (60 × 22 = 1,320). In this case, the pivotal year would shift to the year of the {{ill|Jiazi|ja|甲子}}, three years after Yin Metal Rooster, considered the '''Jiazi Reform Year''' ({{ill|Jiazi Reform|ja|甲子革令}}). This places the starting point at {{ill|664|ja|664年}} AD, the year after the {{ill|Battle of Baekgang|ja|白村江の戦い}}, aligning with the legendary founding date of 660 BC.

==Yin Metal Rooster Month and Day==
A '''Yin Metal Rooster month''' occurs in {{ill|August|ja|8月}} of years ending in 3 or 8 (corresponding to Heavenly Stems {{ill|Gui|ja|癸}} and {{ill|Wu|ja|戊}}). Depending on the calendar system, this could refer to the {{ill|lunar calendar|ja|旧暦|1=Old Lunar Calendar}} month or the solar term period between {{ill|White Dew|ja|白露}} and the day before {{ill|Cold Dew|ja|寒露}}.

A '''Yin Metal Rooster day''' is the 7th day in the {{ill|Hassen|ja|八専}} sequence, excluding intercalary days.

