During the Meiji era, scholar {{ill|Naka Michiyo|ja|那珂通世|12=draft}} referenced ''Kakumei Kanbun'' with {{ill|Zheng Xuan|ja|鄭玄|12=draft}}’s annotation: 
* “The way of Heaven is not distant; after every three and five, it returns. Six cycles ({{ill|Jiazi|ja|甲子|12=draft}}) form one era, four sixes and two sixes overlap, and three sevens multiply to form 21 cycles, totaling 1,320 years.”

Based on this, it was believed that every '''1,260 years''' (21 cycles × 60 years = 1,260, called ''Ichibu'') there would be a major revolution during a Yin Metal Rooster year. Applying this, Naka theorized that the 9th year of {{ill|Empress Suiko|ja|推古天皇|12=draft}}’s reign ({{ill|601|ja|601st year|12=draft}}) marked such a revolutionary year, suggesting that Emperor {{ill|Jimmu|ja|神武天皇|12=draft}}’s enthronement occurred 1,260 years earlier, in {{ill|660 BC|ja|紀元前660th year|12=draft}}.

Alternatively, some interpret the annotation as indicating a '''1,320-year cycle''' (60 × 22 = 1,320). In this case, the pivotal year would shift to the year of the {{ill|Jiazi|ja|甲子|12=draft}}, three years after Yin Metal Rooster, considered the '''Jiazi Reform Year''' ({{ill|Jiazi Reform|ja|甲子革令|12=draft}}). This places the starting point at {{ill|664|ja|664th year|12=draft}} AD, the year after the {{ill|Battle of Baekgang|ja|白村江の戦い|12=draft}}, aligning with the legendary founding date of 660 BC.

==Yin Metal Rooster Month and Day==
A '''Yin Metal Rooster month''' occurs in {{ill|August|ja|8月|12=draft}} of years ending in 3 or 8 (corresponding to Heavenly Stems {{ill|Gui|ja|癸|1=Mizunoto (癸)|12=draft}} and {{ill|Wu|ja|戊|1=Tsuchinoe (戊)|12=draft}}). Depending on the calendar system, this could refer to the {{ill|lunar calendar|ja|旧暦|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|11=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|12=draft}} month or the solar term period between {{ill|White Dew|ja|白露|12=draft}} and the day before {{ill|Cold Dew|ja|寒露|12=draft}}.

A '''Yin Metal Rooster day''' is the 7th day in the {{ill|Hassen|ja|八専|12=draft}} sequence, excluding intercalary days.

